"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843642","Home Office","false","2018-02-22","<p>Over 850 UK-linked individuals of national security concern travelled to engage with the conflict in Syria and Iraq. We estimate that over 15 percent of those who travelled have been killed in fighting in the region and just under half have returned to the UK. Anybody who does return will be investigated by the police to determine if they have committed criminal offences or pose a risk to national security. Those who travelled to, or remained in Syria or Iraq from 2014 are more likely to be a current national security concern than those who travelled and returned before then. While it would not be appropriate to provide a breakdown of the investigation status of travellers or returners, a significant proportion of those individuals who have already returned fall into the latter category and have been assessed as posing little or no national security concern.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843642/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-22T13:27:15.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843642/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843642/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-19","British Nationals Abroad: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people with links to the UK who travelled to engage in the recent conflict in Syria and Iraq have been classified as not being a security concern.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","127983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843643","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>Recruiting for the Army is delivered through the Recruiting Partnering Project; a 10 year output based contractual arrangement with a commercial partner. Under this partnership the costs of recruitment to Defence are shown below. These costs include recruiting services, IT systems, military salaries and infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£182 million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£136 million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£148 million</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures are single service estimates and are not official statistics produced by Defence Statistics.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843643/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:52:35.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843643/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843643/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average cost of recruitment to the Army was in each of the last three full years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843644","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The average cost of recruiting per enlistment in each of the last three years is shown in the table below. This cost is not determined by the age of the individual.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cost Per Enlistment</p></td><td><p>£13,000</p></td><td><p>£10,000</p></td><td><p>£12,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Basic Training for Regular soldiers is delivered in four core training units: the Army Foundation College (Harrogate) which provides for most recruits under 18 (Junior Entry) and Infantry Training Centre (Catterick), Army Training Centre (Pirbright) and Army Training Regiment (Winchester) for Senior Entry training. Some under 18 recruits who are close enough to their 18<sup>th</sup> birthday conduct training in Standard Entry and therefore costs are not held by age. The average cost per Army recruit of providing Basic Training in these units is shown below:</p><p> </p><p>Army Foundation College (Harrogate):</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Junior Entry (Long)</p></td><td><p>£87,000</p></td><td><p>£86,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Junior Entry (Short)</p></td><td><p>£39,000</p></td><td><p>£37,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Initial Training Centre Catterick (ITC) and Army Training Centre Pirbright (ATC(P))/ Army Training Regiment Winchester (ATR(W)):</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ITC</p></td><td><p>£28,000</p></td><td><p>£27,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ATC(P)/ATR(W)</p></td><td><p>£33,000</p></td><td><p>£31,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>All figures are single service estimates and are not official statistics produced by Defence Statistics. Information in this format is only available for the last two years due to a change in information systems used to record the information.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843644/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:51:57.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843644/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843644/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average cost per Army recruit was of (a) recruiting and (b) providing Phase 1 training for recruits (i) under 18 years and (ii) 18 years or above in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843645","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The average cost per recruit of non-military training at the Army Foundation College in each of the last three years is shown below.</p><p> </p><p>Non-military training has been determined as the cost of functional skills education provision, BTEC qualifications and the sports and skills package delivered in the evening.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average cost per recruit</p></td><td><p>£2,872</p></td><td><p>£2,267</p></td><td><p>£2,773</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures are single service estimates and are not official statistics produced by Defence Statistics.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843645/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T14:33:42.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843645/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843645/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average cost per recruit to the Army Foundation College, Harrogate, for non-military training and education was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843646","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The requested information is provided in the attached table, excluding data on minimum initial service periods which could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127988","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843646/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:38:25.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843646/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843646/answer","20180223-PQs02519 21-TABLE - SUBMITTED.xlsx","20180223-PQs02519 21-TABLE - SUBMITTED.xlsx","Stats on Under and Over 18's Service Personnel","Stats on Under and Over 18's Service Personnel","11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of recruits who enlisted aged (a) under 18 and (b) over 18 years left the armed forces before completing (i) phase two training and (ii) the minimum initial service period in each of the last three full years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843647","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The requested information is provided in the attached table, excluding data on minimum initial service periods which could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127987","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843647/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:38:25.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843647/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843647/answer","20180223-PQs02519 21-TABLE - SUBMITTED.xlsx","20180223-PQs02519 21-TABLE - SUBMITTED.xlsx","Stats on Under and Over 18's Service Personnel","Stats on Under and Over 18's Service Personnel","11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, (a) how many  and (b) what proportion of recruits who enlisted aged (i) under 18 and (ii) over 18 years left the armed forces within four years of joining in each of the last three full years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843648","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>As at 1 October 2017 there were 69 Armed Forces personnel in the trained strength under 18 years. This is less than 0.1% of the total trained strength. Under 18s in the trained strength cannot be deployed on front line operations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843648/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T14:39:47.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843648/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843648/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Armed Forces: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of armed forces personnel in the trained strength are under 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843649","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The average length of service for a soldier who enlists aged over 18 years old is nine years and nine months. The average for a soldier enlisting under 18 years old is 13 years and two months.</p><p>For an infantry soldier who enlists aged over 18 years old, the average length of service is eight years and two months. The average for an infantry soldier enlisting under 18 years old is 11 years and two months.</p><p><strong>Notes: </strong></p><p>The figures exclude Ghurkhas, Full Time Reserve Service and Mobilised Reserves. This also excludes any soldiers who do not complete Initial Trade Training.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127991","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843649/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T14:34:45.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843649/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843649/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average length of service is for a soldier who enlists (a) aged over 18 years and (b) below 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843650","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The average length of service for a soldier who enlists aged over 18 years old is nine years and nine months. The average for a soldier enlisting under 18 years old is 13 years and two months.</p><p>For an infantry soldier who enlists aged over 18 years old, the average length of service is eight years and two months. The average for an infantry soldier enlisting under 18 years old is 11 years and two months.</p><p><strong>Notes: </strong></p><p>The figures exclude Ghurkhas, Full Time Reserve Service and Mobilised Reserves. This also excludes any soldiers who do not complete Initial Trade Training.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127990","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843650/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T14:34:45.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843650/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843650/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average length of service is for an infantry soldier who enlists (a) aged over 18 years and (b) below 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843651","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-27","<p>The number of recruits who enlisted, and completed Basic training at the following sites: Army Foundation College (AFC) Harrogate; Army Training Centre (ATC) Pirbright and the Army Training Regiment (ATR) Winchester; and the number of recruits who enlisted Basic training and completed Initial Trade training at Infantry Training Centre (ITC) Catterick are shown below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>AFC Harrogate</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Enlisted Basic Training</strong></p></td><td><p>1,329</p></td><td><p>1,377</p></td><td><p>1,415</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Completed Basic Training</strong></p></td><td><p>1,006</p></td><td><p>1,036</p></td><td><p>1,096</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>ATC Pirbright</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Enlisted Basic Training</strong></p></td><td><p>2,716</p></td><td><p>2,798</p></td><td><p>2,763</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Completed Basic Training</strong></p></td><td><p>1,911</p></td><td><p>2,314</p></td><td><p>2,330</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>ATR Winchester</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Enlisted Basic Training </strong></p></td><td><p>1,063</p></td><td><p>1,185</p></td><td><p>1,010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Completed Basic Training</strong></p></td><td><p>884</p></td><td><p>947</p></td><td><p>868</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>ITC Catterick</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Enlisted Basic Training </strong></p></td><td><p>2,178</p></td><td><p>2,141</p></td><td><p>1,741</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Completed Basic and Initial Trade Training</strong></p></td><td><p>1,495</p></td><td><p>1,750</p></td><td><p>1,637</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures are single service estimates and are not official statistics produced by Defence Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>Army Training Regiment (ATR) Bassingbourn was closed in August 2012. The above information does not represent cohorts, for example recruits will often complete training the following financial year.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843651/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T14:30:10.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843651/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843651/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recruits (a) enlisted at and (b) completed Phase 1 training at (i) AFC Harrogate (ii) ATC Pirbright (iii) ATR Bassingbourn (iv) ITC Catterick in each of the last three full years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843652","Department for Education","false","2018-02-22","<p>I have regular meetings with the Education and Skills Funding Agency, including considering what further action may be necessary in respect of learners affected by the failure of these providers. I have asked the Student Loans Company to write to those learners to advise them of next steps.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843652/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-22T17:07:07.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843652/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843652/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-19","Further Education: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2018 to Question 126486, on further education: loans, what discussions he or Ministers of his Department have had with the (a) Student Loans Company and (b) Education and Skills Funding Agency on that matter.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","127993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843653","Department for Education","false","2018-02-22","<p>Approximately half of the loan-funded learners affected by the contract terminations of John Frank Training Limited, Edudo Limited and Focus Training &amp; Development Limited have transferred to other providers to continue their studies. 180 have not transferred.</p><p> </p><p>The Student Loans Company will be writing shortly to all those affected regarding next steps.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843653/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-22T16:58:53.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843653/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843653/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-19","Further Education: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2018 to Question 126486 on further education: loans, how many learners do not have a new provider.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","127994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843654","Department for Education","false","2018-02-22","<p>The department’s priority when a training provider is no longer delivering courses is to make sure any learners affected can continue with their studies with minimal disruption.</p><p> </p><p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency, working with the Student Loans Company, will seek to identify suitable alternative providers where learners can complete their studies. We are committed to offering, as far as is practicable, a solution for each learner. The resources available for this are kept under review.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843654/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-22T17:00:38.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843654/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843654/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-19","Further Education: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2018 to Question 126486 on further education: loans, what additional resources his Department has allocated to help learners find new providers.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","127995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843655","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-27","<p>Following discussions between my Department’s officials, HS2 Ltd and the Cycle Proofing Working Group (CPWG), HS2 Ltd has shared extracts of its relevant design standards with the CPWG, setting out the obligations and expectations on designers to apply specific cycling standards and guidelines. The discussions also addressed how HS2 Ltd is discharging commitments given to the Cyclists’ Touring Club (CTC), now Cycling UK.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843655/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T16:19:37.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843655/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843655/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the outcome was of discussions between his Department, HS2 Ltd and the cycle-proofing working group on HS2 Ltd’s design standards.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","127996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843656","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-27","<p>HS2 Ltd’s contractors are required to comply with HS2’s technical standards during the design of all works associated with the HS2 programme. HS2’s <em>Technical Standard for Roads</em> specifically refers to Transport for London's <em>London Cycle Design Standards</em> and the Welsh Government's <em>Design Guidance: Active Travel (Wales) Act 2013</em>. HS2 Ltd’s technical standards also include good design practice guidance from other established industry design standards.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843656/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T16:22:12.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843656/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843656/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has assessed HS2 Ltd’s design standards for temporary and permanent changes to on-and off-road highway infrastructure against (a) Transport for London’s London cycling design standards and (b) the Welsh Government’s Active Travel (Wales) Act 2013 design standards.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","127997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843657","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-27","<p>In 2013, the Department commissioned a feasibility study into the potential for new and improved cycle routes within the HS2 corridor. The outputs of the study have been shared with relevant local authorities and will be discussed at future meetings of the Cycle Proofing Working Group.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843657/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T16:25:10.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843657/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843657/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department’s cycle-proofing working group has identified locations where cycle access along or across the HS2 corridor should be maintained or enhanced.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","127998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843658","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-27","<p>HS2 Ltd has set clear requirements for its supply chain to follow, as set out in the HS2 Phase 1 Route-wide Traffic Management Plan. These requirements include:-</p><p> </p><p>a) Vehicles attending worksites are required to comply with the Construction Logistics and Community Safety (CLOCS) standard with regard to the fitment and operation of safety equipment. Principal contractors are required to show how they will provide and operate vehicles which minimise ground clearance, remove blind spots, prevent underrunning and address driver visibility.</p><p> </p><p>b) Construction drivers regularly accessing HS2 construction sites are required to demonstrate that they have attended accredited courses in work-related road risk driver training, rural driver training and fuel efficiency training.</p><p> </p><p>c) Principal contractors are required to adhere to a quality standard, such as the Freight Operator Recognition Scheme, and to show how standards will be implemented through their supply chain.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843658/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T15:58:33.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843658/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843658/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps HS2 Ltd has taken to ensure the safety (a) of cyclists in relation to the design of lorries, (b) awareness of lorry drivers and (c) accreditation of lorry operators involved in HS2-related contracts.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","127999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843659","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-27","<p>A feasibility study into the potential for new and improved cycle routes in the HS2 corridor was commissioned in 2013. The Department has made the outputs from this study available to relevant highway authorities. These include a volume of potential designs for additional cycle links between sites of interest in proximity to the route of the railway. Authorities are encouraged to incorporate these into their Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recently allocated £30m to Local Authorities along the Phase One route for them to spend on road safety. It is for local authorities to determine their local priorities, but the Department has encouraged them to consider funding cycling projects where appropriate.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843659/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-27T16:06:22.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843659/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843659/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to support highway authorities on the HS2 route to provide joined-up cycling infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","128000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843660","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>We are working closely with the Home Office and Ministry of Justice in finalising the consultation, which will be published shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843660/answer",,,,,,,,,,,,"2018-02-22T16:25:12.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843660/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/843660/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-19","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish the consultation to review the effectiveness of current enforcement against unauthorised developments and encampments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","128001"
